# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tcl-tk-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Expect is used to automate control of interactive applications such as Telnet, FTP, passwd, fsck, rlogin, tip, SSH, and others.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Expect uses pseudo terminals (Unix) or emulates a console (Windows), starts the target program, and then communicates with it, just as a human would, via the terminal or console interface.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Tk, another Tcl extension, can be used to provide a GUI.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Expect serves as a "glue" to link existing utilities together.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] The general idea is to figure out how to make Expect use the system's existing tools rather than figure out how to solve a problem inside of Expect.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] A key usage of Expect involves commercial software products.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Many of these products provide some type of command-line interface, but these usually lack the power needed to write scripts.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] They were built to service the users administering the product, but the company often does not spend the resources to fully implement a robust scripting language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] An Expect script can spawn a shell, look up environmental variables, perform some Unix commands to retrieve more information, and then enter into the product's command-line interface armed with the necessary information to achieve the user's goal.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] After retrieving information by interacting with the product via its command-line interface, the script can make intelligent decisions about what action to take, if any.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Every time an Expect operation is completed, the results are stored in a local variable called $expect_out.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] This allows the script to harvest information to feedback to the user, and it also allows conditional behavior of what to send next based on the circumstances.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] A common use of Expect is to set up a testing suite for programs, utilities or embedded systems.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] DejaGnu is a testing suite written using Expect for use in testing.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] It has been used for testing GCC and remote targets such as embedded development.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Expect script can be automated using a tool called 'autoexpect'.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] This tool observes your actions and generates an Expect script using heuristics.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Though generated code may be large and somewhat cryptic, one can always tweak the generated script to get the exact code.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Using passwords as command-line arguments, like in this example, is a huge security hole, as any other user on the machine can read this password by running "ps".
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] You can, however, add code that will prompt you for your password rather than giving your password as an argument.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] Various projects implement Expect-like functionality in other languages, such as C#, Java, Scala, Groovy, Perl, Python, Ruby, Shell and Go.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/expect] These are generally not exact clones of the original Expect, but the concepts tend to be very similar.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/glue-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ousterhout was previously a professor of computer science at University of California, Berkeley, where he created the Tcl scripting language and the Tk platform-independent widget toolkit, and proposed the idea of coscheduling.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ousterhout led the research group that designed the experimental Sprite operating system and the first log-structured file system.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ousterhout also led the team that developed the Magic VLSI computer-aided design (CAD) program.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] He received a Bachelor of Science (B.S.) in physics from Yale University in 1975, and his Ph.D. in computer science from Carnegie Mellon University in 1980.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ousterhout received the Grace Murray Hopper Award in 1987 for his work on electronic design automation CAD systems for very-large-scale integrated circuits.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] For the same work, he was inducted in 1994 as a Fellow of the Association for Computing Machinery.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ousterhout was elected a member of the National Academy of Engineering in 2001 for improving our ability to program computers by raising the level of abstraction.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] In 1994, Ousterhout left Berkeley to join Sun Microsystems Laboratories, which hired a team to join him in Tcl development.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] After several years at Sun, he left and co-founded Scriptics, Inc.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] (later renamed Ajuba Solutions) in January 1998 to provide professional Tcl development tools.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Most of the Tcl team followed him from Sun.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] Ajuba was purchased by Interwoven in October 2000.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/john-ousterhout] He joined the faculty of Stanford University in 2008.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk provides many widgets commonly needed to develop desktop applications, such as button, menu, canvas, text, frame, label, etc.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk has been ported to run on most flavors of Linux, macOS, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Like Tcl, Tk 8.6 supports Unicode within the Basic Multilingual Plane, while Tk 9 supports the full Unicode range.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk was designed to be extended, and a wide range of extensions are available that offer new widgets or other capabilities.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Since Tcl/Tk 8, it offers "native look and feel" (for instance, menus and buttons are displayed in the manner of "native" software for any given platform).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Highlights of version 8.5 include a new theming engine, originally called Tk Tile, but it is now generally referred to as "themed Tk", as well as improved font rendering.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Highlights of version 8.6 include PNG support and angled text.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk was developed by John Ousterhout as an extension for the Tcl scripting language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk versioning was done separately from Tcl until version 8.0.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk was written originally for Unix/X11, and proved extremely popular with programmers in the 1990s by virtue of its being easier to learn and use than Motif and other X11 toolkits of the time.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk was also ported to Microsoft Windows and Macintosh platforms, starting with Tk 4.2 and improved with native look and feel in Tk 8.0 (released 1997).
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Interest in Tk waned significantly from the late 1990s and onward.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] The default look and feel on Unix still emulated Motif, despite the mainstream replacement of Motif by toolkits such as FLTK, Qt, and GTK.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Widgets that became commonly used in applications (e.g. trees, combo boxes, tabbed notebooks) were not available in the Tk core, but only via multiple, often competing add-ons.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk 8.5, released in late 2007, corrected some of these problems by adding missing widgets to the core, introducing a new theming engine and modernizing the look and feel on Unix.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] However, because some code changes were required to incorporate these advancements, many existing applications retain the older Motif-inspired feel that Tk had become known for.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Tk is a platform-independent GUI framework developed for Tcl.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] From a Tcl shell (tclsh), Tk may be invoked using the command `package require Tk`.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] The program wish (WIndowing SHell) provides a way to run a tclsh shell in a graphical window as well as providing Tk.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] A library written in one programming language may be used in another language if bindings are written; Tk is integrated with the Tcl language.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Various other languages have bindings for Tk, a partial list of which is on the Tk website.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Bindings exist for additional languages which might not be listed, including Ada (called TASH), Go (through tk9.0), Haskell (called HTk), Perl, Python (called Tkinter), R (through the standard package: tcltk), Ruby, Rexx, and Common Lisp.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] There are several ways to use Tk from Perl: the Tcl::Tk and Tkx Perl modules, both of which use Tcl as a bridge to access Tk, and Perl/Tk, which provides native Perl access to Tk structures.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] The Python binding uses Tcl as a bridge to Tk.
[src:tcl-tk-deep/tk-software] Basic widgets are embedded into `toplevel` widgets, which in turn are usually hosted by the operating system in floating windows that can be moved around on the screen.
